Correct.

9. What is an online learning system?
An online learning system represents a system that can be trained incrementally
using mini-batches. These systems require less io, data, memory, disk space and cpu than traditional
off-line learning systems that needs to be implemented through batch-learning.
Each learning is fast and cheap. These methods are great for systems
that needs to learn incrementally or that receives data as a continous flow
(e.g. stocks). It is also a good system if you have limited resources.
A challenge is that if bad data is loaded into the system the performance will decline
faster than a corresponding off-line solution.
Correct.

10. What is out-of-core learning
Online systems can also be used to train systems on huge data-sets that cannot
fit in one machines memory. This is called out-of-core learning.
Correct.

11. Instance-based learning system learns the training data by heart; then, when it
is given a new instance, it uses a similarity measure to find the most similarity
learned instance and them make predictions. An example of such a model is k-nearest neighbours
or k-means clustering.
Correct.

12. The hyper-parameter is part of the model calibration an not the model. The
hyper-parameter is fixed before training is commenced and remains fixed during
its duration. Hyper-parameters can be used for regularization or finetuning a calibration.
Correct.

13. Model based learning algorithms search for an optimal value for the model
parameters such that the model will generalize well to new instances.
Models are usually trained by minimising a cost-function that measures how bad the system
is at making predictions on the training data, plus a penalty for model complexity
if the model is regularized.
Correct, but rewritten.

